<br />

<h2 class="pen"></h2>

<div class="post">

<div class="entrytext">

	<p>I&#8217;ve always been a fan of sports team nicknames. At one point a few years back (for some reason) I collected every team name I could find. Finding the stories behind the names would have been a fun task, but apparently Emerson Houk beat me to the punch with his book<a href="http://www.indystar.com/articles/9/098706-4639-047.html">&#8220;Go Huskies! Beat Felix the Cat!&#8221;</a></p>

	<p>It should prove to be entertaining, the link is to an Indy Star article. Here&#8217;s a snipet:</p>

	<p>&#8220;Houck didn&#8217;t realize just how peculiar and possibly telling a mascot could be until just a few years ago, when he and his wife were meandering toward St. Louis&#8230;</p>

	<p>He loved being greeted by signs that announced he was entering, say, &#8220;Austin: Where Eagles Soar.&#8221; He liked the display of pride.</p>

	<p>He was struck particularly when, heading to St. Louis, he pulled into the Illinois town of Teutopolis, &#8220;Home of the Wooden Shoes.&#8221; The same day he found himself in Effingham, &#8220;Home of the Flaming Hearts,&#8221; and then to Vandalia, &#8220;Home of the Vandals,&#8221; Roxanna, &#8220;Home of the Shells,&#8221; and finally, Centralia, &#8220;Home of the Orphans.&#8221;</p>

	<p>&#8220;That&#8217;s when I dug in,&#8221; Houck says. He says that in 1922, Centralia had a basketball team that reached the state championship in Champaign, where a sportswriter wrote that the Centralians &#8220;played like champs but looked like orphans.&#8221;</p>

	<p>The school, which did not then have a mascot, embraced the snub.</p>

	<p>Years later, when girls&#8217; teams came into being, those teams were not the &#8220;Lady Orphans,&#8221; they were the &#8220;Annies.&#8221;</p>

	<p>Fun stuff</p>



 

<p class="postmetadata alt">

